   "source": [
    "## Hypothesis\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We hypothesize that broadband internet access is positively associated with employment status and annual earnings among U.S. adults aged 25–54. Individuals with household broadband subscriptions are expected tohave better labor-market outcomes, as internet connectivity facilitates job search, remote work, and access to employment opportunities."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Data overview\n",
    "\n",
    "This project uses the **Current Population Survey (CPS) Computer and Internet Use Supplement 2023** dataset released by the U.S. Census Bureau. The CPS is one of the most important labor force surveys in the United States and is conducted jointly by the U.S. Census Bureau and the Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS).\n",
    "\n",
    "The November 2023 Computer and Internet Use Supplement adds questions related to internet access, internet usage locations, and digital device usage.\n",
    "\n",
    "Using this dataset, we aim to explore the relationship between internet usage behavior and labor market outcomes such as employment status and hourly earnings, while also considering demographic characteristics.\n",
    "\n",
    "This dataset provides nationally representative microdata collected from households across the United States.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Dataset\n",
    "\n",
    "**Dataset Name:**  \n",
    "Current Population Survey (CPS) Computer and Internet Use Supplement 2023\n",
    "\n",
    "**Source:**  \n",
    "https://www.census.gov/data/datasets/2023/demo/cps/cps-computer.html\n",
    "\n",
    "**Number of Observations:**  \n",
    "126,917 individual observations from household survey data.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Number of Variables:**  \n",
    "The raw dataset contains 554 variables. After cleaning and selection, we retain 26 variables relevant to our research question.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Relevant Variables\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Demographic variables\n",
    "- age\n",
    "- sex\n",
    "- race\n",
    "- education\n",
    "- marital_status\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Geographic variables\n",
    "- state_fips\n",
    "- metro_status\n",
    "- cbsa_code\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Labor market variables\n",
    "- labor_force_status_major\n",
    "- hourly_earnings\n",
    "- industry_major_recode\n",
    "- occupation_major_recode\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Device usage variables\n",
    "- use_laptop\n",
    "- use_desktop\n",
    "- use_tablet\n",
    "- use_smartphone\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Internet usage location variables\n",
    "- internet_at_home\n",
    "- internet_at_work\n",
    "- internet_at_school\n",
    "- internet_at_cafe\n",
    "- internet_while_traveling\n",
    "- internet_at_library_or_community\n",
    "- internet_elsewhere_home\n",
    "- internet_other_places\n",
    "\n",
    "## Shortcomings\n",
    "\n",
    "This dataset has several limitations:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Self-report bias**  \n",
    "   Internet usage behavior and income information are self-reported by respondents, which may introduce measurement errors.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. **Limited population coverage for some variables**  \n",
    "   Some variables apply only to specific groups (for example, hourly earnings only apply to employed individuals), which may lead to missing or special coded values.\n",
    "\n",
    "3. **Cross-sectional data**  \n",
    "   The dataset reflects information from a single point in time, which limits the ability to infer causal relationships.\n",
    "\n",
    "4. **Internet usage variables are categorical**  \n",
    "   Internet usage variables mainly indicate whether the internet is used in certain locations rather than precise usage time or frequency.\n"
   ]
  },
